[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] In mathematics, a real-valued function is called **convex** if the line segment between any two distinct points on the graph of the function lies above or on the graph of the function between the two points.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Equivalently, a function is convex if its *epigraph* (the set of points on or above the graph of the function) is a convex set.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] In simple terms, a convex function graph is shaped like a cup $\cup$ (or a straight line like a linear function), while a concave function's graph is shaped like a cap $\cap$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A twice-differentiable function of a single variable is convex if and only if its second derivative is nonnegative on its entire domain.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Well-known examples of convex functions of a single variable include a linear function $f(x)=cx$ (where c is a real number), a quadratic function $cx^{2}$ ( c as a nonnegative real number) and an exponential function $ce^{x}$ ( c as a nonnegative real number).
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Convex functions play an important role in many areas of mathematics.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] They are especially important in the study of optimization problems where they are distinguished by a number of convenient properties.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] For instance, a strictly convex function on an open set has no more than one minimum.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Even in infinite-dimensional spaces, under suitable additional hypotheses, convex functions continue to satisfy such properties and as a result, they are the most well-understood functionals in the calculus of variations.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] In probability theory, a convex function applied to the expected value of a random variable is always bounded above by the expected value of the convex function of the random variable.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] This result, known as Jensen's inequality, can be used to deduce inequalities such as the arithmetic–geometric mean inequality and Hölder's inequality.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Let X be a convex subset of a real vector space and let $f:X\to \mathbb {R}$ be a function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] The sum $-\infty +\infty$ is also undefined so a convex extended real-valued function is typically only allowed to take exactly one of $-\infty$ and $+\infty$ as a value.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A strictly convex function f is a function such that the straight line between any pair of points on the curve f is above the curve f except for the intersection points between the straight line and the curve.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] An example of a function which is convex but not strictly convex is $f(x,y)=x^{2}+y$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] This function is not strictly convex because any two points sharing an x coordinate will have a straight line between them, while any two points NOT sharing an x coordinate will have a greater value of the function than the points between them.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] The function f is said to be ***concave*** (resp.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] ***strictly concave***) if $-f$ ( f multiplied by −1) is convex (resp. strictly convex).
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] The term *convex* is often referred to as *convex down* or *concave upward*, and the term concave is often referred as *concave down* or *convex upward*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] If the term "convex" is used without an "up" or "down" keyword, then it refers strictly to a cup shaped graph $\cup$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] As an example, Jensen's inequality refers to an inequality involving a convex or convex-(down), function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Many properties of convex functions have the same simple formulation for functions of many variables as for functions of one variable.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] See below the properties for the case of many variables, as some of them are not listed for functions of one variable.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] The concept of strong convexity extends and parametrizes the notion of strict convexity.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Intuitively, a strongly-convex function is a function that grows as fast as a quadratic function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A strongly convex function is also strictly convex, but not vice versa.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] For example, let f be strictly convex, and suppose there is a sequence of points $(x_{n})$ such that $f''(x_{n})={\tfrac {1}{n}}$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Even though $f''(x_{n})>0$ , the function is not strongly convex because $f''(x)$ will become arbitrarily small.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Some authors, such as refer to functions satisfying this inequality as elliptic functions.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] It is not necessary for a function to be differentiable in order to be strongly convex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Notice that this definition approaches the definition for strict convexity as $m\to 0,$ and is identical to the definition of a convex function when $m=0.$ Despite this, functions exist that are strictly convex but are not strongly convex for any $m>0$ (see example below).
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] This is equivalent to requiring that the minimum eigenvalue of $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ be at least m for all $x.$ If the domain is just the real line, then $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ is just the second derivative $f''(x),$ so the condition becomes $f''(x)\geq m$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] If $m=0$ then this means the Hessian is positive semidefinite (or if the domain is the real line, it means that $f''(x)\geq 0$ ), which implies the function is convex, and perhaps strictly convex, but not strongly convex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Assuming still that the function is twice continuously differentiable, one can show that the lower bound of $\nabla ^{2}f(x)$ implies that it is strongly convex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A function f is strongly convex with parameter *m* if and only if the function $x\mapsto f(x)-{\frac {m}{2}}\|x\|^{2}$ is convex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A twice continuously differentiable function f on a compact domain X that satisfies $f''(x)>0$ for all $x\in X$ is strongly convex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] The proof of this statement follows from the extreme value theorem, which states that a continuous function on a compact set has a maximum and minimum.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Strongly convex functions are in general easier to work with than convex or strictly convex functions, since they are a smaller class.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] Like strictly convex functions, strongly convex functions have unique minima on compact sets.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] A uniformly convex function, with modulus $\phi$ , is a function f that, for all $x,y$ in the domain and $t\in [0,1],$ satisfies $f(tx+(1-t)y)\leq tf(x)+(1-t)f(y)-t(1-t)\phi (\|x-y\|)$ where $\phi$ is a function that is non-negative and vanishes only at 0.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] This is a generalization of the concept of strongly convex function; by taking $\phi (\alpha )={\tfrac {m}{2}}\alpha ^{2}$ we recover the definition of strong convexity.
[src:li-chao-envelope/convex-function] It is worth noting that some authors require the modulus $\phi$ to be an increasing function, but this condition is not required by all authors.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] In combinatorics, a **Davenport–Schinzel sequence** is a sequence of symbols in which the number of times any two symbols may appear in alternation is limited.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] The maximum possible length of a Davenport–Schinzel sequence is bounded by the number of its distinct symbols multiplied by a small but nonconstant factor that depends on the number of alternations that are allowed.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Davenport–Schinzel sequences were first defined in 1965 by Harold Davenport and Andrzej Schinzel to analyze linear differential equations.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Following Atallah (1985) these sequences and their length bounds have also become a standard tool in discrete geometry and in the analysis of geometric algorithms.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] If *x* and *y* are two distinct values occurring in the sequence, then the sequence does not contain a subsequence ...
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] is a Davenport–Schinzel sequence of order 3: it contains alternating subsequences of length four, such as ...1, ...
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] (which appears in four different ways as a subsequence of the whole sequence) but it does not contain any alternating subsequences of length five.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] If a Davenport–Schinzel sequence of order *s* includes *n* distinct values, it is called an (*n*,*s*) Davenport–Schinzel sequence, or a *DS*(*n*,*s*)-sequence.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] The complexity of *DS*(*n*,*s*)-sequence has been analyzed asymptotically in the limit as *n* goes to infinity, with the assumption that *s* is a fixed constant, and nearly tight bounds are known for all *s*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Let *λ**s*(*n*) denote the length of the longest *DS*(*n*,*s*)-sequence.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Due to the very rapid growth of the Ackermann function, its inverse α grows very slowly, and is at most four for problems of any practical size.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] When *s* is a function of *n* the upper and lower bounds on Davenport-Schinzel sequences are not tight.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Suppose that these functions are particularly well behaved: they are all continuous, and any two of them are equal on at most *s* values.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] With these assumptions, the real line can be partitioned into finitely many intervals within which one function has values smaller than all of the other functions.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] The sequence of these intervals, labeled by the minimizing function within each interval, forms a Davenport–Schinzel sequence of order *s*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Thus, any upper bound on the complexity of a Davenport–Schinzel sequence of this order also bounds the number of intervals in this representation of the lower envelope.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] In the original application of Davenport and Schinzel, the functions under consideration were a set of different solutions to the same homogeneous linear differential equation of order *s*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/davenport-schinzel-sequence] Any two distinct solutions can have at most *s* values in common, so the lower envelope of a set of *n* distinct solutions forms a *DS*(*n*,*s*)-sequence.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In both contexts it refers to simplifying a complicated problem by breaking it down into simpler sub-problems in a recursive manner.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] While some decision problems cannot be taken apart this way, decisions that span several points in time do often break apart recursively.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Likewise, in computer science, if a problem can be solved optimally by breaking it into sub-problems and then recursively finding the optimal solutions to the sub-problems, then it is said to have *optimal substructure*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If sub-problems can be nested recursively inside larger problems, so that dynamic programming methods are applicable, then there is a relation between the value of the larger problem and the values of the sub-problems.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In the optimization literature this relationship is called the Bellman equation.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In terms of mathematical optimization, dynamic programming usually refers to simplifying a decision by breaking it down into a sequence of decision steps over time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This is done by defining a sequence of **value functions** *V*1, *V*2, ..., *V**n* taking *y* as an argument representing the **state** of the system at times *i* from 1 to *n*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The definition of *V**n*(*y*) is the value obtained in state *y* at the last time *n*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The values *V**i* at earlier times *i* = *n* −1, *n* − 2, ..., 2, 1 can be found by working backwards, using a recursive relationship called the Bellman equation.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For *i* = 2, ..., *n*, *V**i*−1 at any state *y* is calculated from *V**i* by maximizing a simple function (usually the sum) of the gain from a decision at time *i* − 1 and the function *V**i* at the new state of the system if this decision is made.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Since *V**i* has already been calculated for the needed states, the above operation yields *V**i*−1 for those states.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Finally, *V*1 at the initial state of the system is the value of the optimal solution.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The optimal values of the decision variables can be recovered, one by one, by tracking back the calculations already performed.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The solution to this problem is an optimal control law or policy $\mathbf {u} ^{\ast }=h(\mathbf {x} (t),t)$ , which produces an optimal trajectory $\mathbf {x} ^{\ast }$ and a cost-to-go function $J^{\ast }$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In practice, this generally requires numerical techniques for some discrete approximation to the exact optimization relationship.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] at the k -th stage of n equally spaced discrete time intervals, and where ${\hat {f}}$ and ${\hat {\mathbf {g} }}$ denote discrete approximations to f and $\mathbf {g}$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This functional equation is known as the Bellman equation, which can be solved for an exact solution of the discrete approximation of the optimization equation.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In economics, the objective is generally to maximize (rather than minimize) some dynamic social welfare function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In Ramsey's problem, this function relates amounts of consumption to levels of utility.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Loosely speaking, the planner faces the trade-off between contemporaneous consumption and future consumption (via investment in capital stock that is used in production), known as intertemporal choice.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Future consumption is discounted at a constant rate $\beta \in (0,1)$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] where c is consumption, k is capital, and f is a production function satisfying the Inada conditions.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] An initial capital stock $k_{0}>0$ is assumed.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let $c_{t}$ be consumption in period t, and assume consumption yields utility $u(c_{t})=\ln(c_{t})$ as long as the consumer lives.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Assume the consumer is impatient, so that he discounts future utility by a factor b each period, where $0<b<1$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Assume initial capital is a given amount $k_{0}>0$ , and suppose that this period's capital and consumption determine next period's capital as $k_{t+1}=Ak_{t}^{a}-c_{t}$ , where A is a positive constant and $0<a<1$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Written this way, the problem looks complicated, because it involves solving for all the choice variables $c_{0},c_{1},c_{2},\ldots ,c_{T}$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming approach to solve this problem involves breaking it apart into a sequence of smaller decisions.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] To do so, we define a sequence of *value functions* $V_{t}(k)$ , for $t=0,1,2,\ldots ,T,T+1$ which represent the value of having any amount of capital k at each time t.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] There is (by assumption) no utility from having capital after death, $V_{T+1}(k)=0$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The value of any quantity of capital at any previous time can be calculated by backward induction using the Bellman equation.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This problem is much simpler than the one we wrote down before, because it involves only two decision variables, $c_{t}$ and $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Intuitively, instead of choosing his whole lifetime plan at birth, the consumer can take things one step at a time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] At time t, his current capital $k_{t}$ is given, and he only needs to choose current consumption $c_{t}$ and saving $k_{t+1}$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] To actually solve this problem, we work backwards.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For simplicity, the current level of capital is denoted as k. $V_{T+1}(k)$ is already known, so using the Bellman equation once we can calculate $V_{T}(k)$ , and so on until we get to $V_{0}(k)$ , which is the *value* of the initial decision problem for the whole lifetime.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] We see that it is optimal to consume a larger fraction of current wealth as one gets older, finally consuming all remaining wealth in period T, the last period of life.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] There are two key attributes that a problem must have in order for dynamic programming to be applicable: optimal substructure and overlapping sub-problems.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If a problem can be solved by combining optimal solutions to *non-overlapping* sub-problems, the strategy is called "divide and conquer" instead.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This is why merge sort and quick sort are not classified as dynamic programming problems.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Some programming languages can automatically memoize the result of a function call with a particular set of arguments, in order to speed up call-by-name evaluation (this mechanism is referred to as *call-by-need*).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Some languages make it possible portably (e.g.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Some languages have automatic memoization built in, such as tabled Prolog and J, which supports memoization with the *M.* adverb.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In any case, this is only possible for a referentially transparent function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Memoization is also encountered as an easily accessible design pattern within term-rewrite based languages such as Wolfram Language.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming is widely used in bioinformatics for tasks such as sequence alignment, protein folding, RNA structure prediction and protein-DNA binding.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The first dynamic programming algorithms for protein-DNA binding were developed in the 1970s independently by Charles DeLisi in the US and by Georgii Gurskii and Alexander Zasedatelev in the Soviet Union.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Recently these algorithms have become very popular in bioinformatics and computational biology, particularly in the studies of nucleosome positioning and transcription factor binding.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm for the shortest path problem is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's famous Principle of Optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Using dynamic programming in the calculation of the *n*th member of the Fibonacci sequence improves its performance greatly.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In particular, `fib(2)` was calculated three times from scratch.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In larger examples, many more values of `fib`, or *subproblems*, are recalculated, leading to an exponential time algorithm.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Now, suppose we have a simple map object, *m*, which maps each value of `fib` that has already been calculated to its result, and we modify our function to use it and update it.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This technique of saving values that have already been calculated is called *memoization*; this is the top-down approach, since we first break the problem into subproblems and then calculate and store values.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In the **bottom-up** approach, we calculate the smaller values of `fib` first, then build larger values from them.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This method also uses O(*n*) time since it contains a loop that repeats n − 1 times, but it only takes constant (O(1)) space, in contrast to the top-down approach which requires O(*n*) space to store the map.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In both examples, we only calculate `fib(2)` one time, and then use it to calculate both `fib(4)` and `fib(3)`, instead of computing it every time either of them is evaluated.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Consider the problem of assigning values, either zero or one, to the positions of an *n* × *n* matrix, with *n* even, so that each row and each column contains exactly *n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] We ask how many different assignments there are for a given n.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] There are at least three possible approaches: brute force, backtracking, and dynamic programming.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Brute force consists of checking all assignments of zeros and ones and counting those that have balanced rows and columns (*n* / 2 zeros and *n* / 2 ones).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] As there are $2^{n^{2}}$ possible assignments and ${\tbinom {n}{n/2}}^{n}$ sensible assignments, this strategy is not practical for arbitrarily large values of n .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Backtracking for this problem consists of choosing some order of the matrix elements and recursively placing ones or zeros, while checking that in every row and column the number of elements that have not been assigned plus the number of ones or zeros are both at least *n* / 2.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] While more sophisticated than brute force, this approach will visit every solution once, making it impractical for *n* larger than six, since the number of solutions is already 116963796250 for *n* = 8, as we shall see.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Dynamic programming makes it possible to count the number of solutions without visiting them all.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Imagine backtracking values for the first row – what information would we require about the remaining rows, in order to be able to accurately count the solutions obtained for each first row value?
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] We consider *k* × *n* boards, where 1 ≤ *k* ≤ *n*, whose k rows contain $n/2$ zeros and $n/2$ ones.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The function *f* to which memoization is applied maps vectors of *n* pairs of integers to the number of admissible boards (solutions).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] There is one pair for each column, and its two components indicate respectively the number of zeros and ones that have yet to be placed in that column.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If any one of the results is negative, then the assignment is invalid and does not contribute to the set of solutions (recursion stops).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Otherwise, we have an assignment for the top row of the *k* × *n* board and recursively compute the number of solutions to the remaining (*k* − 1) × *n* board, adding the numbers of solutions for every admissible assignment of the top row and returning the sum, which is being memoized.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The base case is the trivial subproblem, which occurs for a 1 × *n* board.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The number of solutions for this board is either zero or one, depending on whether the vector is a permutation of *n* / 2 (0, 1) and *n* / 2 (1, 0) pairs or not.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Links to the MAPLE implementation of the dynamic programming approach may be found among the external links.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Consider a checkerboard with *n* × *n* squares and a cost function `c(i, j)` which returns a cost associated with square `(i,j)` (`*i*` being the row, `*j*` being the column).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This problem exhibits **optimal substructure**.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] That is, the solution to the entire problem relies on solutions to subproblems.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Starting at rank `n` and descending to rank `1`, we compute the value of this function for all the squares at each successive rank.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Picking the square that holds the minimum value at each rank gives us the shortest path between rank `n` and rank `1`.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The function `q(i, j)` is equal to the minimum cost to get to any of the three squares below it (since those are the only squares that can reach it) plus `c(i, j)`.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The first line of this equation deals with a board modeled as squares indexed on `1` at the lowest bound and `n` at the highest bound.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The second line specifies what happens at the first rank; providing a base case.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The third line, the recursion, is the important part.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] It represents the `A,B,C,D` terms in the example.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] From this definition we can derive straightforward recursive code for `q(i, j)`.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This function only computes the path cost, not the actual path.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This, like the Fibonacci-numbers example, is horribly slow because it too exhibits the **overlapping sub-problems** attribute.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] That is, it recomputes the same path costs over and over.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] However, we can compute it much faster in a bottom-up fashion if we store path costs in a two-dimensional array `q[i, j]` rather than using a function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This avoids recomputation; all the values needed for array `q[i, j]` are computed ahead of time only once.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Precomputed values for `(i,j)` are simply looked up whenever needed.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] We also need to know what the actual shortest path is.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] To do this, we use another array `p[i, j]`; a *predecessor array*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This array records the path to any square `s`.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The predecessor of `s` is modeled as an offset relative to the index (in `q[i, j]`) of the precomputed path cost of `s`.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] To reconstruct the complete path, we lookup the predecessor of `s`, then the predecessor of that square, then the predecessor of that square, and so on recursively, until we reach the starting square.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Now the rest is a simple matter of finding the minimum and printing it.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In genetics, sequence alignment is an important application where dynamic programming is essential.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Typically, the problem consists of transforming one sequence into another using edit operations that replace, insert, or remove an element.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Each operation has an associated cost, and the goal is to find the sequence of edits with the lowest total cost.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] 3. replacing the first character of A with the first character of B, and performing optimal alignments of the tails of A and B.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The partial alignments can be tabulated in a matrix, where cell (i,j) contains the cost of the optimal alignment of A[1..i] to B[1..j].
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The cost in cell (i,j) can be calculated by adding the cost of the relevant operations to the cost of its neighboring cells, and selecting the optimum.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Different variants exist, see Smith–Waterman algorithm and Needleman–Wunsch algorithm.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The **Tower of Hanoi** or **Towers of Hanoi** is a mathematical game or puzzle.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] It consists of three rods, and a number of disks of different sizes which can slide onto any rod.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The puzzle starts with the disks in a neat stack in ascending order of size on one rod, the smallest at the top, thus making a conical shape.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] S(n, h, t) := solution to a problem consisting of n disks that are to be moved from rod h to rod t.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For n=1 the problem is trivial, namely S(1,h,t) = "move a disk from rod h to rod t" (there is only one disk left).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The number of moves required by this solution is 2*n* − 1.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If the objective is to **maximize** the number of moves (without cycling) then the dynamic programming functional equation is slightly more complicated and 3*n* − 1 moves are required.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] A famous puzzle relates to dropping eggs from a building to determine at which height they start to break.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] terminology, in which the first floor is at ground level).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If only one egg is available and we wish to be sure of obtaining the right result, the experiment can be carried out in only one way.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Drop the egg from the first-floor window; if it survives, drop it from the second-floor window.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] In the worst case, this method may require 36 droppings.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] What is the lowest number of egg-droppings that is guaranteed to work in all cases?
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For instance, *s* = (2,6) indicates that two test eggs are available and 6 (consecutive) floors are yet to be tested.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The initial state of the process is *s* = (*N*,*H*) where *N* denotes the number of test eggs available at the commencement of the experiment.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The process terminates either when there are no more test eggs (*n* = 0) or when *k* = 0, whichever occurs first.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If termination occurs at state *s* = (0,*k*) and *k* > 0, then the test failed.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] It is easy to solve this equation iteratively by systematically increasing the values of *n* and *k*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Notice that the above solution takes $O(nk^{2})$ time with a DP solution.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This can be improved to $O(nk\log k)$ time by binary searching on the optimal x in the above recurrence, since $W(n-1,x-1)$ is increasing in x while $W(n,k-x)$ is decreasing in x , thus a local minimum of $\max(W(n-1,x-1),W(n,k-x))$ is a global minimum.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Also, by storing the optimal x for each cell in the DP table and referring to its value for the previous cell, the optimal x for each cell can be found in constant time, improving it to $O(nk)$ time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let k be the total number of floors such that the eggs break when dropped from the k th floor (The example above is equivalent to taking $k=37$ ).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let m be the minimum floor from which the egg must be dropped to be broken.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let $f(t,n)$ be the maximum number of values of m that are distinguishable using t tries and n eggs.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let a be the floor from which the first egg is dropped in the optimal strategy.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If the first egg broke, m is from 1 to a and distinguishable using at most $t-1$ tries and $n-1$ eggs.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If the first egg did not break, m is from $a+1$ to k and distinguishable using $t-1$ tries and n eggs.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Then the problem is equivalent to finding the minimum x such that $f(x,n)\geq k$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] To do so, we could compute $\{f(t,i):0\leq i\leq n\}$ in order of increasing t , which would take $O(nx)$ time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Thus, if we separately handle the case of $n=1$ , the algorithm would take $O(n{\sqrt {k}})$ time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] But the recurrence relation can in fact be solved, giving $f(t,n)=\sum _{i=0}^{n}{\binom {t}{i}}$ , which can be computed in $O(n)$ time using the identity ${\binom {t}{i+1}}={\binom {t}{i}}{\frac {t-i}{i+1}}$ for all $i\geq 0$ .
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Since $f(t,n)\leq f(t+1,n)$ for all $t\geq 0$ , we can binary search on t to find x , giving an $O(n\log k)$ algorithm.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Matrix chain multiplication is a well-known example that demonstrates utility of dynamic programming.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For example, engineering applications often have to multiply a chain of matrices.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] It is not surprising to find matrices of large dimensions, for example 100×100.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Matrix multiplication is not commutative, but is associative; and we can multiply only two matrices at a time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] There are numerous ways to multiply this chain of matrices.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] They will all produce the same final result, however they will take more or less time to compute, based on which particular matrices are multiplied.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] If matrix A has dimensions m×n and matrix B has dimensions n×q, then matrix C=A×B will have dimensions m×q, and will require m*n*q scalar multiplications (using a simplistic matrix multiplication algorithm for purposes of illustration).
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] For example, let us multiply matrices A, B and C.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let us assume that their dimensions are m×n, n×p, and p×s, respectively.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] (A×B)×C This order of matrix multiplication will require mnp + mps scalar calculations.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] So, the first way to multiply the chain will require 1,000,000 + 1,000,000 calculations.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The second way will require only 10,000 + 100,000 calculations.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Obviously, the second way is faster, and we should multiply the matrices using that arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Therefore, our conclusion is that the order of parenthesis matters, and that our task is to find the optimal order of parenthesis.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] At this point, we have several choices, one of which is to design a dynamic programming algorithm that will split the problem into overlapping problems and calculate the optimal arrangement of parenthesis.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The dynamic programming solution is presented below.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Let's call m[i,j] the minimum number of scalar multiplications needed to multiply a chain of matrices from matrix i to matrix j (i.e.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] We split the chain at some matrix k, such that i <= k < j, and try to find out which combination produces minimum m[i,j].
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] So far, we have calculated values for all possible *m*[*i*, *j*], the minimum number of calculations to multiply a chain from matrix *i* to matrix *j*, and we have recorded the corresponding "split point"*s*[*i*, *j*].
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This algorithm will produce "tables" *m*[, ] and *s*[, ] that will have entries for all possible values of i and j.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The final solution for the entire chain is m[1, n], with corresponding split at s[1, n].
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Unraveling the solution will be recursive, starting from the top and continuing until we reach the base case, i.e. multiplication of single matrices.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Therefore, the next step is to actually split the chain, i.e. to place the parenthesis where they (optimally) belong.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Of course, this algorithm is not useful for actual multiplication.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This algorithm is just a user-friendly way to see what the result looks like.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The term *dynamic programming* was originally used in the 1940s by Richard Bellman to describe the process of solving problems where one needs to find the best decisions one after another.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] By 1953, he refined this to the modern meaning, referring specifically to nesting smaller decision problems inside larger decisions, and the field was thereafter recognized by the IEEE as a systems analysis and engineering topic.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Bellman's contribution is remembered in the name of the Bellman equation, a central result of dynamic programming which restates an optimization problem in recursive form.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The word *dynamic* was chosen by Bellman to capture the time-varying aspect of the problems, and because it sounded impressive.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The word *programming* referred to the use of the method to find an optimal *program*, in the sense of a military schedule for training or logistics.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] This usage is the same as that in the phrases *linear programming* and *mathematical programming*, a synonym for mathematical optimization.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] The above explanation of the origin of the term may be inaccurate: According to Russell and Norvig, the above story "cannot be strictly true, because his first paper using the term (Bellman, 1952) appeared before Wilson became Secretary of Defense in 1953." Also, Harold J.
[src:li-chao-envelope/dynamic-programming] Kushner stated in a speech that, "On the other hand, when I asked [Bellman] the same question, he replied that he was trying to upstage Dantzig's linear programming by adding dynamic.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] In calculus, analytic geometry and related areas, a linear function is a polynomial of degree one or less, including the zero polynomial.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] where *a* and *b* are constants, often real numbers.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] The graph of such a function of one variable is a nonvertical line.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] *a* is frequently referred to as the slope of the line, and *b* as the intercept.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] If *a > 0* then the gradient is positive and the graph slopes upwards.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] If *a < 0* then the gradient is negative and the graph slopes downwards.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] and the graph is a hyperplane of dimension *k*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] A constant function is also considered linear in this context, as it is a polynomial of degree zero or is the zero polynomial.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] Its graph, when there is only one variable, is a horizontal line.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] In this context, a function that is also a linear map (the other meaning of linear functions, see below) may be referred to as a homogeneous linear function or a linear form.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] In the context of linear algebra, the polynomial functions of degree 0 or 1 are the scalar-valued affine maps.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] Here *a* denotes a constant belonging to the field *K* of scalars (for example, the real numbers), and **x** and **y** are elements of $\mathbf {V}$ , which might be *K* itself.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] Even if the same symbol + is used, the operation of addition between **x** and **y** (belonging to $\mathbf {V}$ ) is not necessarily same to the operation of addition between $f\left(\mathbf {x} \right)$ and $f\left(\mathbf {y} \right)$ (belonging to $\mathbf {W}$ ).
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] In other terms the linear function preserves vector addition and scalar multiplication.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] Some authors use "linear function" only for linear maps that take values in the scalar field; these are more commonly called linear forms.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] The "linear functions" of calculus qualify as "linear maps" when (and only when) *f*(0, ..., 0) = 0, or, equivalently, when the constant b equals zero in the one-degree polynomial above.
[src:li-chao-envelope/linear-function] Geometrically, the graph of the function must pass through the origin.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] In mathematics, the **lower envelope** or **pointwise minimum** of a finite set of functions is the pointwise minimum of the functions, the function whose value at every point is the minimum of the values of the functions in the given set.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] The concept of a lower envelope can also be extended to partial functions by taking the minimum only among functions that have values at the point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] The **upper envelope** or **pointwise maximum** is defined symmetrically.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] For an infinite set of functions, the same notions may be defined using the infimum in place of the minimum, and the supremum in place of the maximum.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] For continuous functions from a given class, the lower or upper envelope is a piecewise function whose pieces are from the same class.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] For convex functions or quasiconvex functions, the upper envelope is again convex or quasiconvex.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] The lower envelope is not, but can be replaced by the lower convex envelope to obtain an operation analogous to the lower envelope that maintains convexity.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] The upper and lower envelopes of Lipschitz functions preserve the property of being Lipschitz.
[src:li-chao-envelope/lower-envelope] However, the lower and upper envelope operations do not necessarily preserve the property of being a continuous function.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] In computer science, the **segment tree** is a data structure used for storing information about intervals or segments.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] It allows querying which of the stored segments contain a given point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] A similar data structure is the interval tree.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] A segment tree for a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage and can be built in *O*(*n* log *n*) time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Segment trees support searching for all the intervals that contain a query point in time *O*(log *n* + *k*), *k* being the number of retrieved intervals or segments.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Applications of the segment tree are in the areas of computational geometry, geographic information systems and machine learning.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Let I be a set of intervals, or segments.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Let *p*1, *p*2, ..., *pm* be the list of distinct interval endpoints, sorted from left to right.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Consider the partitioning of the real line induced by those points.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The regions of this partitioning are called *elementary intervals*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] That is, the list of elementary intervals consists of open intervals between two consecutive endpoints *pi* and *p**i*+1, alternated with closed intervals consisting of a single endpoint.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Single points are treated themselves as intervals because the answer to a query is not necessarily the same at the interior of an elementary interval and its endpoints.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] A segment tree from the set of segments I, can be built as follows.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] First, the endpoints of the intervals in I are sorted.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The elementary intervals are obtained from that.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Then, a balanced binary tree is built on the elementary intervals, and for each node *v* it is determined the interval Int(*v*) it represents.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] It remains to compute the canonical subsets for the nodes.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] To achieve this, the intervals in I are inserted one by one into the segment tree.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The complete construction operation takes *O*(*n* log *n*) time, *n* being the number of segments in I.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Visiting every node takes constant time (assuming that canonical subsets are stored in a simple data structure like a linked list).
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] When we visit node *v*, we either store *X* at *v*, or Int(*v*) contains an endpoint of *X*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] As proved above, an interval is stored at most twice at each level of the tree.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] There is also at most one node at every level whose corresponding interval contains *x*, and one node whose interval contains *x′*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] So, at most four nodes per level are visited.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Since there are *O*(log *n*) levels, the total cost of the insertion is *O*(log *n*).
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] A query for a segment tree receives a point *qx*(should be one of the leaves of tree), and retrieves a list of all the segments stored which contain the point *qx*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] In a segment tree that contains *n* intervals, those containing a given query point can be reported in *O*(log *n* + *k*) time, where *k* is the number of reported intervals.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The query algorithm visits one node per level of the tree, so *O*(log *n*) nodes in total.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] On the other hand, at a node *v*, the segments in I are reported in *O*(1 + *kv*) time, where *kv* is the number of intervals at node *v*, reported.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The sum of all the *kv* for all nodes *v* visited, is *k*, the number of reported segments.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] A segment tree *T* on a set I of *n* intervals uses *O*(*n* log *n*) storage.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Let *v*1, *v*2, *v*3 be the three nodes at the same depth, numbered from left to right; and let p(*v*) be the parent node of any given node *v*.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] This means that [*x*, *x′*] spans the whole interval from the left endpoint of Int(*v*1) to the right endpoint of Int(*v*3).
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Note that all segments at a particular level are non-overlapping and ordered from left to right: this is true by construction for the level containing the leaves, and the property is not lost when moving from any level to the one above it by combining pairs of adjacent segments.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Now either parent(*v*2) = parent(*v*1), or the former is to the right of the latter (edges in the tree do not cross).
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] In the first case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is the same as Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point; in the second case, Int(parent(*v*2))'s leftmost point is to the right of Int(parent(*v*1))'s rightmost point, and therefore also to the right of Int(*v*1)'s rightmost point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] In both cases, Int(parent(*v*2)) begins at or to the right of Int(*v*1)'s leftmost point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Similar reasoning shows that Int(parent(*v*2)) ends at or to the left of Int(*v*3)'s rightmost point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] Int(parent(*v*2)) must therefore be contained in [*x*, *x′*]; hence, [*x*, *x′*] will not be stored at *v*2.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The segment tree can be generalized to higher dimension spaces, in the form of multi-level segment trees.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] In higher dimensional versions, the segment tree stores a collection of axis-parallel (hyper-)rectangles, and can retrieve the rectangles that contain a given query point.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The structure uses *O*(*n* log*d* *n*) storage, and answers queries in *O*(log*d* *n*) time.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The use of fractional cascading lowers the query time bound by a logarithmic factor.
[src:li-chao-envelope/segment-tree] The use of the interval tree on the deepest level of associated structures lowers the storage bound by a logarithmic factor.
